name: Sanford's White-eye
rangeDescription: Woodland and scrub of nendö (northern temotu, southeastern solomon islands)
description: A distinctive white-eye, mostly dark brown above and buff below. Note the large black beady eye with a broad pale eye-ring, the long yellow bill, and the yellow legs.

name: Pin-tailed Snipe
rangeDescription: Siberia; winters india to southeastern asia, indonesia, and philippines
description: Cryptic shorebird of wetlands, wet meadows, and both flooded and dry agricultural fields. Extremely similar in appearance to other snipe, particularly Swinhoe's Snipe; careful study and photography usually required to confirm identification.

name: Tufted Antshrike
rangeDescription: Southeastern brazil to eastern paraguay and far northeastern argentina (misiones)
description: Medium-sized antshrike, with a long tail and a crest. Found in the understory and middle levels of humid forests with dense vine tangles or bamboo and in second growth areas.

name: Spot-backed Antshrike
rangeDescription: Southeastern brazil to eastern paraguay and far northeastern argentina (misiones)
description: Chunky antshrike with a long tail and heavy bill with a hooked tip. Males are spotted black and white above (buffier in females) and brownish below with a barred tail.

name: Spice Imperial-Pigeon
rangeDescription: Widi island (off halmahera) and raja ampat islands (off western new guinea)
description: A large, stocky pigeon that is found on islands off the shore of Halmahera and far western Papua. Gray head, emerald-green back and wings, blue tail and rusty vent.

name: Icterine Warbler
rangeDescription: Central europe to western siberia and northern iran; winters to southern africa
description: Medium-sized warbler, light olive-brown above and yellowish below. Distinctive features include longish, daggerlike bill, long primary projection in the wings, and square tail.

name: Buru Honeyeater
rangeDescription: Mountains of buru (southern moluccas)
description: A medium-sized, largely olive-brown songbird with a striking yellow base to the downcurved bill, a thin yellow line from bill to eye, and dull bare skin behind the eye. Found in foothills and mountains, within forest, forest edge, and scrub as singles and pairs, and also joins mixed-species flocks.

name: Rufous-cheeked Tanager
rangeDescription: Coastal mountains of northern venezuela (southern lara to distrito federal)
description: Beautiful aquamarine tanager with rufous mask. Several shades of blue on body: back is darker aquamarine, underparts mostly turquoise, belly cream, and undertail cinnamon.

name: Yellow-shouldered Grassquit
rangeDescription: Hills and mountains of jamaica
description: A small seed-eating species of forest edges, open woodlands, and nearby weedy areas; usually found in groups of two to five birds. Both sexes have bright yellow-green shoulders and a buff vent, which are diagnostic but can be difficult to see.

name: White-bellied Sunbird
rangeDescription: Southwestern angola and northern namibia eastward to southeastern tanzania, zambia, malawi, northern and eastern botswana, zimbabwe, mozambique, eswatini, and eastern south africa (north west and limpopo to free state and kwazulu-natal)
description: A small, pale-bellied sunbird. The male has iridescent blue-green upperparts and head, with a bold white belly and broad purplish breast band.

name: Western Bonelli's Warbler
rangeDescription: Western and central europe; winters to sahel of northern africa
description: Small, sleek warbler; white belly contrasts with olive and green upperparts. Very difficult to separate from Eastern Bonelli’s of Eastern Europe.

name: Stresemann's Bush-Crow
rangeDescription: Southern ethiopia (sidamo province)
description: An unusual small crow-like bird with gray, black, and white plumage. There is bright blue bare skin around the eye, and sometimes a small pink patch is also visible behind the eye.

name: Chestnut-winged Chachalaca
rangeDescription: Woodland and scrub of northern colombia
description: Long-tailed, chickenlike bird restricted to the lowlands of northern Colombia. The chestnut wings may be hidden from view when the bird is perched.

name: Blue Lorikeet
rangeDescription: Society islands, cook islands, and western tuamotu archipelago
description: A unique and distinctive lorikeet, almost entirely a deep royal blue with a bright orange bill and feet and an extensive pure white throat, cheek, and chest patch. Inhabits any forest, but appears to favor coconut and banana plantations.

name: Pale-winged Starling
rangeDescription: Desert of southwestern angola to namibia and arid interior south africa
description: A large glossy-black starling that shows whitish wing patches in flight. Pairs and small groups are resident in semi-desert and desert, where they prefer rocky areas and cliffs, but they also occur in towns and scrubland foraging for fruit and invertebrates.

name: Bismarck Honeyeater
rangeDescription: Mountains of central new britain (southeastern bismarck archipelago)
description: A relatively distinctive honeyeater, olive-brown overall with a darker cast to the face and obvious pale bare skin surrounding and extending slightly behind the eye. Bill is long and conspicuously downturned.

name: Red-throated Pipit
rangeDescription: Tundra of northern palearctic and northwestern alaska; winters to africa, indonesia, and philippines
description: Small pipit; adults distinctive with rusty-red face and throat (paler in winter), contrasting with streaked white belly. The back is heavily streaked black, white, and brown, and the rump is also streaked.

name: Cinereous Mourner
rangeDescription: Eastern colombia to venezuela, eastern brazil, northern bolivia, and amazonian brazil
description: Medium-sized gray bird of rainforest midstory. Similar to Screaming Piha and Grayish Mourner, but has small orange spots on the shoulder and narrow yellow eye ring (those species are entirely gray).

name: Curl-crested Aracari
rangeDescription: Eastern peru to northern bolivia and western amazonian brazil south of the amazon
description: Heavy-billed small toucan of humid tropical forest. Forages in the canopy of mature rainforest, often in small groups, and sometimes with other species of aracaris.

name: St. Lucia Warbler
rangeDescription: St. lucia (lesser antilles)
description: This small brightly colored bird feeds actively within middle to upper levels of forests. The combination of blue-gray upperparts, extensively yellow underparts, white wingbars, and bold facial pattern are unique within its range.
